rning on actual evapotranspiration estimation in the scarcely observed region","paper_id":"10.1016/j.jhydrol.2022.127506","doi":"10.1016/j.jhydrol.2022.127506","authors":"Wang, Xiaoshu; Gao, Bing; Wang, Xu-Sheng"}},"end":{"id":"454","labels":["Uncertainty"],"properties":{"name":"Measurement","definition":"Sensor errors, resolution limits, missing data, or measurement noise.","uncertainty_code":"U2"}}}
{"type":"relationship","id":"6931053020662727111","label":"REPORTS_UNCERTAINTY","properties":{"description":"Model simulation errors and correlation biases in input lead-times."},"start":{"id":"331","labels":["Paper"],"properties":{"is_data_fusion_paper":"Yes","source_group":"32","classification_reason":"Included in the structured extraction workbook as a fusion-related paper.","publication_title":"JOURNAL OF HYDROLOGY","publication_date":"2022","source_type":"bibliography + structured spreadsheet","abstract":"The estimation of actual evapotranspiration is a difficult issue in hydrological research, particularly in the scarcely observed region. Deep learning (DL) has been increasingly used in the field of hydrology in recent years. In this study, we investigated the ability of DL on actual evapotranspiration estimation using three sets of controlled experiments at a typical region with scarce observations, the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau. The results suggest that the DL model can utilize a few key types of observation data to simulate actual evapotranspiration, and more in-situ observation data types did not significantly improve the accuracy of DL simulations. A multisource DL model established by integrating data from distantly distributed stations showed a better performance than the model built separately using data at individual sites. Moreover, further analysis of climate pattern and input data correlation was conducted for the similarity of stations for multi-source learning of the DL model. Using inputs in the lead-time period can improve the simulation of daily ET by DL. Compared with traditional process-based physical methods, the DL model is more flexible to simulate actual evapotranspiration in areas with insufficient observed data such as the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau. The results of this study highlight the potential power of DL model to improve the actual evapotranspiration estimation in the scarcely observed region.","title":"Investigating the ability of deep learning on actual evapotranspiration estimation in the scarcely observed region","paper_id":"10.1016/j.jhydrol.2022.127506","doi":"10.1016/j.jhydrol.2022.127506","authors":"Wang, Xiaoshu; Gao, Bing; Wang, Xu-Sheng"}},"end":{"id":"455","labels":["Uncertainty"],"properties":{"name":"Analysis","definition":"Algorithmic assumptions, model bias, or processing errors.","uncertainty_code":"U3"}}}
{"type":"relationship","id":"1152929201188241740","label":"USES_METHOD","start":{"id":"332","labels":["Paper"],"properties":{"is_data_fusion_paper":"Yes","source_group":"32","classification_reason":"Included in the structured extraction workbook as a fusion-related paper.","publication_title":"GAIT \\& POSTURE","publication_date":"2022","source_type":"bibliography + structured spreadsheet","abstract":"Background: There is a range of magneto-inertial measurement unit (MIMU) systems commercially available, however sensor specifications and fusion methods vary considerably between manufacturers. Such variability can influence the concurrent validity of MIMUs relative to reference standard measurement devices. Different MIMUs have been compared during static or low-velocity conditions, with higher-velocity movements assessed in robotic-based studies. However, there is a need for the concurrent validity of higher-velocity movements to be established in human-based studies. Research question: This study aimed to assess the concurrent validity of two commercial MIMU systems (Noraxon and Xsens), relative to a `gold-standard' retro-reflective motion capture system, when measuring trunk angles during uni-planar range of motion (ROM) and cricket bowling, which involves high-speed, multi-planar movements. Methods: For this criterion-based validity study, both MIMU systems incorporated comparable sensor specificaotions and employed Kalman filter sensor fusion algorithms. The MIMU based angles were compared with angles derived from concurrently captured three-dimensional retro-reflective data for 10 fast-medium bowlers. Statisotical parametric mapping and root mean squared differences (RMSD) were computed for both MIMU systems. Results: One-dimensional statistical parametric mapping showed no significant differences for angles from both MIMU systems when compared with retro-reflective based angle outputs. The MIMU systems produced ROM RMSDs between 1.4 +/- 1.0. and 2.6 +/- 1.5.. One system displayed RMSDs between 4.6 +/- 1.4. and 7.4 +/- 1.9. during bowling, indicating functionally relevant differences to retro-reflective derived angles. There were some small but statistically significant differences in RMSDs between the MIMU systems. Significance: MIMU-based angle accuracy is poorer during high-speed, multi-planar movement than uni-planar tasks. Comparable MIMU systems can produce varying measurements during ROM and bowling tasks. It is likely that varying sample rates and sensor fusion algorithm parameters contributed to the differences.","title":"Measurement of uni-planar and sport specific trunk motion using magneto-inertial measurement units: The concurrent validity of Noraxon and Xsens systems relative to a retro-reflective system","paper_id":"10.1016/j.gaitpost.2021.11.012","doi":"10.1016/j.gaitpost.2021.11.012","authors":"Cottam, Daniel S.; Campbell, Amity C.; Davey, Paul C.; Kent, Peter; Elliott, Bruce C.; Alderson, Jacqueline A."}},"end":{"id":"358","labels":["Method"],"properties":{"methodKey":"M_6378fa24c950","source_group":"32","method_id":"M_6378fa24c950","name":"Kalman Filter (Noraxon/Xsens)","extraction_source":"structured spreadsheet","description":"Sensor fusion for merging MIMU data for trunk motion analysis.","method_key_original":"M_KALMAN_C22"}}}
{"type":"relationship","id":"1152930300699869516","label":"MENTIONS_DATASET","start":{"id":"332","labels":["Paper"],"properties":{"is_data_fusion_paper":"Yes","source_group":"32","classification_reason":"Included in the structured extraction workbook as a fusion-related paper.","publication_title":"GAIT \\& POSTURE","publication_date":"2022","source_type":"bibliography + structured spreadsheet","abstract":"Background: There is a range of magneto-inertial measurement unit (MIMU) systems commercially available, however sensor specifications and fusion methods vary considerably between manufacturers. Such variability can influence the concurrent validity of MIMUs relative to reference standard measurement devices. Different MIMUs have been compared during static or low-velocity conditions, with higher-velocity movements assessed in robotic-based studies. However, there is a need for the concurrent validity of higher-velocity movements to be established in human-based studies. Research question: This study aimed to assess the concurrent validity of two commercial MIMU systems (Noraxon and Xsens), relative to a `gold-standard' retro-reflective motion capture system, when measuring trunk angles during uni-planar range of motion (ROM) and cricket bowling, which involves high-speed, multi-planar movements. Methods: For this criterion-based validity study, both MIMU systems incorporated comparable sensor specificaotions and employed Kalman filter sensor fusion algorithms. The MIMU based angles were compared with angles derived from concurrently captured three-dimensional retro-reflective data for 10 fast-medium bowlers. Statisotical parametric mapping and root mean squared differences (RMSD) were computed for both MIMU systems. Results: One-dimensional statistical parametric mapping showed no significant differences for angles from both MIMU systems when compared with retro-reflective based angle outputs. The MIMU systems produced ROM RMSDs between 1.4 +/- 1.0. and 2.6 +/- 1.5.. One system displayed RMSDs between 4.6 +/- 1.4. and 7.4 +/- 1.9. during bowling, indicating functionally relevant differences to retro-reflective derived angles. There were some small but statistically significant differences in RMSDs between the MIMU systems. Significance: MIMU-based angle accuracy is poorer during high-speed, multi-planar movement than uni-planar tasks. Comparable MIMU systems can produce varying measurements during ROM and bowling tasks. It is likely that varying sample rates and sensor fusion algorithm parameters contributed to the differences.","title":"Measurement of uni-planar and sport specific trunk motion using magneto-inertial measurement units: The concurrent validity of Noraxon and Xsens systems relative to a retro-reflective system","paper_id":"10.1016/j.gaitpost.2021.11.012","doi":"10.1016/j.gaitpost.2021.11.012","authors":"Cottam, Daniel S.; Campbell, Amity C.; Davey, Paul C.; Kent, Peter; Elliott, Bruce C.; Alderson, Jacqueline A."}},"end":{"id":"402","labels":["DatasetMention"],"properties":{"source_group":"32","temporal_coverage":"Trial-based (High-freq)","datasetmention_id":"DM_a6fcca071f52","canonical_dataset":"MIMU Inertial Data","name":"MIMU Inertial Data","format":"CSV/Binary","extraction_source":"structured spreadsheet","data_type":"Inertial (IMU)","spatial_coverage":"Body-worn (Trunk)","sensor_type":"IoT / Sensor","doi":"10.1016/j.gaitpost.2021.11.012"}}}
