{"type":"relationship","id":"1152929201188241744","label":"USES_METHOD","start":{"id":"336","labels":["Paper"],"properties":{"keywords":"Crop quality; Deep learning; Internet of things; Machine learning; Smart farming","source_type":"bibliography + structured spreadsheet","abstract":"The race for automation has reached farms and agricultural fields. Many of these facilities use the Internet of Things technologies to automate processes and increase productivity. Besides, Machine Learning and Deep Learning allow performing continuous decision making based on data analysis. In this work, we fill a gap in the literature and present a novel architecture based on IoT and Machine Learning / Deep Learning technologies for the continuous assessment of agricultural crop quality. This architecture is divided into three layers that work together to gather, process, and analyze data from different sources to evaluate crop quality. In the experiments, the proposed approach based on data aggregation from different sources reaches a lower percentage error than considering only one source. In particular, the percentage error achieved by our approach in the test dataset was 6.59, while the percentage error achieved exclusively using data from sensors was 6.71.","title":"FARMIT: continuous assessment of crop quality using machine learning and deep learning techniques for IoT-based smart farming","paper_id":"10.1007/s10586-021-03489-9","url":"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10586-021-03489-9","field_of_study":"Smart agriculture; IoT; Machine learning; Computer science","is_data_fusion_paper":"Yes","source_group":"33","classification_reason":"Aggregates heterogeneous greenhouse sources including sensors, RGB imagery, QA/tasting measurements, and agronomic logs for crop-quality assessment.","publisher":"Springer Nature","publication_title":"CLUSTER COMPUTING-THE JOURNAL OF NETWORKS SOFTWARE TOOLS AND APPLICATIONS","publication_date":"2022","doi":"10.1007/s10586-021-03489-9","authors":"Perales Gomez, Angel Luis; Lopez-de-Teruel, Pedro E.; Ruiz, Alberto; Garcia-Mateos, Gines; Bernabe Garcia, Gregorio; Garcia Clemente, Felix J."}},"end":{"id":"363","labels":["Method"],"properties":{"methodKey":"M_4b06671398e0","source_group":"33","method_id":"M_4b06671398e0","name":"FARMIT multimodal crop-quality assessment architecture","extraction_source":"structured spreadsheet","description":"A three-layer IoT/ML architecture aggregates traditional greenhouse sensors, RGB image features, QA variables, pest/defect/task records, and temporal context; preprocessing and machine-learning models are then used for continuous crop-quality assessment.","method_key_original":"320d32e9-4f5b-55f8-9220-925d5e2f6ef1"}}}
